data.enText: to speak or say sth in a quiet voice that is difficult to hear, especially because you are annoyed about sth

data.chText: 他轻声嘀咕道：“她怎么敢。”
data.enText: ‘How dare she,’ he muttered under his breath.

data.chText: 她坐在那儿独自唧唧咕咕的。
data.enText: She just sat there muttering to herself.

data.chText: 我嘀咕着说要接着干活了。
data.enText: I muttered something about needing to get back to work.
to complain about sth, without saying publicly what you think

data.chText: 工人私下对资方还是有怨言。
data.enText: Workers continued to mutter about the management.
a quiet sound or words that are difficult to hear

tr: a complaint uttered in a low and indistinct tone
often accompanied by movement of the lips without the production of articulate speech
make complaining remarks or noises under one's breath
example: she grumbles when she feels overworked

value.def: If you mutter, you speak very quietly so that you cannot easily be heard, often because you are complaining about something.

example.ex: 'God knows what's happening in that madman's mind,' she muttered...
example.tran: 她咕哝着：“天知道那个疯子在想什么。”

example.ex: She can hear the old woman muttering about consideration...
example.tran: 她能听到那个老妇人小声咕哝说考虑考虑。

example.ex: He sat there shaking his head, muttering to himself...
example.tran: 他坐在那儿摇着头，小声地自言自语。

example.ex: She was staring into the fire muttering.
example.tran: 她目不转睛地盯着火苗，小声咕哝着。

example.ex: They make no more than a mutter of protest.
example.tran: 他们只不过是低声抗议了一下。

example.ex: He heard muttering from the front of the crowd...
example.tran: 他听到人群前面有人在小声嘀咕什么。

example.ex: He will lead the party into the election, in spite of the mutterings about his leadership.
example.tran: 尽管人们对他的领导颇有微词，他仍将领导其政党参加选举。
